<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/78a02cc5-ecc9-4241-bfe0-f5fc60bd3db6> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Scale-degradation: hybrid is a constant retrieval offset, not a compounding edge (A4 falsified)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Pre-registered STRICT scale-degradation sweep (rust-rfcs, 25 frozen leak-filtered targets, N=50/100/200/400/634, deterministic $0; B1-rag BM25Okapi vs B2 get_relevant_context at floor 0.99 BM25F / 0.50 hybrid; MOOSEDEV_EXPAND_HOPS=0; parity OK + sentinel/anchor canaries rank 1). RESULT: B2 hybrid beats B1-rag at EVERY N (Δ MRR +0.089..+0.178; hit@5 @N=634 = 0.84 vs 0.60) — a real, SUBSTANTIAL CONSTANT offset. BUT the gap does NOT widen with N: Δ slope vs log10(N) β=-0.033 [95% CI -0.124,+0.059] (spans 0); endpoint widening -0.045 (Δ@50 +0.134 -> Δ@634 +0.089, an inverted-U peaking at N=200). Both arms DECAY near-parallel (B1-rag MRR 0.750->0.536; B2@0.50 0.884->0.625). So thesis A4 ('structured edge GROWS with corpus size', Lesson 8a06ad1d) is FALSIFIED for the retrieval-ALGORITHM dimension: the dense channel is a constant lift (Δ_dense +0.10..+0.14), not scaling; at N=634 MOOSE BM25F alone (0.527) slightly TRAILS rank_bm25 (0.536), so the dense channel does all the work keeping B2 ahead. VERDICT per the strict pre-registered rule (β CI includes 0, β<=0, widening<0.05): KILL — but KILL = retrieval-parity-at-SCALE-COMPOUNDING, NOT a project kill and NOT 'no better' (B2 is clearly + substantially better at every N). SCOPE: rust-rfcs is flat/single-kind/all-current, so this tests ONLY the retrieval-algorithm slope (dense vs BM25 — which ANY vector DB has). The MOOSEDev-DISTINCTIVE question — does the STRUCTURAL advantage (type-filtering / graph-traversal / supersession) COMPOUND with N — is UNTESTED here (needs a chains-preserving typed corpus; the flat-rebuild of trivyn-temporal loses its 42 chains, so it needs agentic temporal --limit builds, not $0). ROUTE: next instrument = structural-compounding + the capability/governance dimensions (8a06ad1d B/C), NOT more retrieval-algorithm N. PROCESS WIN: the pre-registered strict bar forced the precise question (does it COMPOUND?) and returned an honest negative; without it the constant offset would have been mis-celebrated as a scale win. Stage-0 necessary-condition (B1-rag decays: β=-0.173, CI excludes 0) held; harness = bench/scale_{targets,build,probe,report}.py + run_scale_degradation.sh." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-22T22:22:15.522296Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Scale-degradation: hybrid is a constant retrieval offset, not a compounding edge (A4 falsified)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/47f3f038-8fd7-4a96-9c74-15a24bf8be17> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/7b41be4f-ff1e-4827-b90f-570e05be8919> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/b933bd10-de56-4481-91dd-397a192a8022> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Phase-2 turf: mem0 wins simple relevance (B2 thrashes), ties currency, loses completeness" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Phase-2 codegraph competitor matrix adds mem0's HOME-TURF dimensions (relevance recall + currency) to the capability classes, so the comparison is balanced — not a strawman that only tests B2's turf. The result is INVERSE TRADES, with data:\n\nSIMPLE RELEVANCE RECALL (mem0's turf) — mem0 WINS on cost + reliability. On 'why does codegraph do X' lookups, B2's agent THRASHED: rel_value_ref_edges run1 = list_mcp_resources dump (945K tokens, cov 0.80), run2 = ZERO queries (answered from priors, cov 0.00); rel_telemetry run1 = 1.17M tokens (cov 0.67), run2 = 57K (cov 0.33). mem0's recall(query) was foolproof + cheap: ~40K tokens, consistent cov 0.67-0.90. So on a pure relevance lookup mem0 is 10-30x cheaper AND more consistent — EMPIRICAL confirmation of the query-competence downside (Lesson f8f2f87c): B2's power tier is overkill the agent misuses, while mem0's trivial skill floor can't be misused. (Caveat: relevance MARKERS were prior-contaminated — cold B0 scored 0.33-0.80 because the answer is derivable from the term — so ABSOLUTE coverage is noisy; the cost+consistency contrast is the robust signal. Cleaner relevance tasks need project-specific non-guessable facts — cf Lesson 046bc2d8 prompt-leak contamination.)\n\nCURRENCY (mem0's temporal turf) — clean TIE. cur_mcp_handshake (real CHANGELOG reversal 'instant MCP handshake'): B1-notes = B1-mem0 = B2 = 1.00 (all serve the current 'no longer hangs' state); cold B0 = 0.00, stale-flagged. All memory arms tie; mem0's temporal reasoning matches.\n\nCOMPLETENESS / NEGATION / SUPERSESSION (B2's turf) — B2 CATEGORICAL, fair + judge-validated. B2 1.00 vs mem0 ~0.15 vs notes ~0.05 (fair LLM-judge recall, coverage method, B2-validated). mem0 surfaces ~15% of a large set (its top-k slice), never the whole.\n\nSYNTHESIS (the honest headline): mem0 and MOOSEDev make INVERSE trades. mem0 = cheap, foolproof, small-context — wins simple relevance, ties currency, but structurally CANNOT do completeness/negation/traversal. MOOSEDev = complete, structured, auditable — wins those categorically, but its payoff is conditional on agent query competence (it thrashed on simple relevance). 'Equals on currency, mem0 wins simple relevance, MOOSEDev wins completeness/structure.' Relates to Lessons f8f2f87c (query-competence), a6529240 (judge fairness), 243c6c89 / 8a06ad1d (capability axis), 046bc2d8 (prompt contamination). Full matrix: bench/EVALUATION_MEM0.md." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-23T17:43:56.273441Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Phase-2 turf: mem0 wins simple relevance (B2 thrashes), ties currency, loses completeness" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/47f3f038-8fd7-4a96-9c74-15a24bf8be17> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Don't index A-box; walk planning for precision" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Pattern: I proposed embedding-ranked A-box recall and embedding-based instance dedup — i.e. building a vector index over instance content. That contradicts a deliberate MOOSE design choice: MOOSE does NOT index instance data; the walk-planning mechanism was devised specifically to avoid the vector-index/RAG trap and deliver more precise, auditable results. Rule: when recall/dedup/contradiction feels like it needs \"semantic search\" over recorded instances, reach for the symbolic path first — query (walk planning) and sparql for retrieval precision; LLM-as-sensor + typed conflict for contradiction (Requirement b5b101dd) — not a nearest-neighbor index over instances. Embeddings in MOOSEDev are confined to T-box term alignment (suggest_parent) over the static ontology, which is class placement, not instance retrieval. Corollary for tool design: get_relevant_context is a shallow lexical anchor/browse tool by construction (resolve-only, no walk); fix its imprecision with an honesty floor + correct tool-selection guidance, never by upgrading it to vector search." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T03:58:13.046896Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Don't index instance data — MOOSE uses walk planning for precision by design" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Value benchmark measures only the retrieval slice" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Honest scoping of the bench (invariant #6). The B0/B1/B2 A-B design grades point-in-time answer accuracy + token cost over a FROZEN graph snapshot — i.e. only the RETRIEVAL slice: given recorded knowledge, can a model find + use it, and how cheaply. Three classes of MOOSEDev's theoretical advantage over markdown/BM25 are OUT OF that frame:\n\nA. LONGITUDINAL (manifest only as a project evolves): (1) currency/anti-staleness — supersede chains keep memory current while markdown+BM25 serve stale (our currency test confounded: records self-describe status and B1 was made currency-aware for fairness); (2) contradiction detection; (3) drift prevention via alignment (canonical concepts vs synonym sprawl across contributors); (4) anti-degradation at scale — BM25 precision DECAYS as N grows and documents share keywords, typed retrieval does not, so the structured edge should GROW with corpus size; (5) confabulation-resistance in CAPTURE — typed schema + grounded links + validation constrain what is recorded, while free text accepts plausible-but-wrong notes forever.\n\nB. CAPABILITY (BM25/markdown cannot express these at all — possible-vs-impossible, not a shared accuracy axis): aggregate/set/structural queries ('all anti-patterns violating a currently-accepted constraint'; 'decisions with no recorded rationale'); transitive reasoning chains at arbitrary depth; global validation (is the memory internally consistent / shape-conformant?); programmatic/symbolic consumers (a CI gate querying recorded constraints, no LLM — invariant #1).\n\nC. TRUST/GOVERNANCE (value is human confidence, not task accuracy): per-claim provenance + auditability; deliberate curation (review/approve/supersede/retract).\n\nWHAT THE BENCH CAN CLAIM: efficiency/delivery (push << cold/pull, robust across regimes) + a NARROW accuracy edge on gated multi-hop. WHAT IT CANNOT: A/B/C. HOW TO APPLY: scope benchmark claims to the retrieval slice; never let a null there read as 'structured memory does not help'; pursue A/B/C with their own instruments — a longitudinal study (a real project on MOOSEDev for months), capability demonstrations (queries BM25 cannot express, shown possible-vs-impossible), and qualitative trust/audit evaluation. Extends v1-value AD 7b824b26; relates to Lessons f2f4cd99 (valid-task-design), 0b2a0f80 (flat graph -> structured~=free-text), fa9170f6 (efficiency matrix), aaee7652 (currency inconclusive), and the active-participant AD 145af7e9 (capture side)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T19:10:12.287893Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8a06ad1d-0edf-490b-a04d-e2ab17502e0f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "The value benchmark measures only the RETRIEVAL slice (point-in-time accuracy + token efficiency); MOOSEDev's longitudinal, capability, and trust benefits are out of its frame — scope claims accordingly" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Don't index A-box; walk planning for recall" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Reaching for an embedding/vector index over recorded instances (A-box) for recall or dedup contradicts a deliberate MOOSE design choice: MOOSE does not index instance data; walk planning avoids the RAG/nearest-neighbor trap and yields more precise, auditable retrieval. Keep embeddings confined to T-box term alignment (suggest_parent) over the static ontology. For instance recall/dedup use query (walk planning) and sparql; for contradiction use LLM-as-sensor plus typed conflict — not a nearest-neighbor index over instances. Evidence: tasks/lessons.md." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "deprecated" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasRationale> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Rationale/558acbcf-5aae-4bfa-9d91-10e2e68ea367> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T05:48:11.044893Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8b275bce-49b1-42ad-8f49-5d65a4ff77ee> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Don't index instance data — MOOSE uses walk planning for precise, auditable recall" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "NLQ bottleneck is the single-shot gate, not labels" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "mcp" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "A new NLQ eval harness (bench/nlq_eval.py + bench/nlq_eval/queries.jsonl, 18 currency/lookup/relation queries graded into correct/wrong/unresolved/clarified) on the dogfood graph shows the NLQ bottleneck is MOOSE Core's single-shot 'needs clarification' GATE (14/18 = 77%), NOT entity resolution: 0/18 unresolved. Every query that passed the gate resolved a record — 3 correct (incl. the A-box bounded-seed CURRENT answer and a 194-triple relation traversal) and 1 thin-wrong. IMPLICATION: skos:altLabel/hiddenLabel additions only help the unresolved/wrong buckets (0+1 of 18), so they have ~no target right now; the lever is the Core gate, which over-aggressively rejects reasonable questions ('what is the title convention', 'how does get_relevant_context retrieve', 'what is BENCH_WORK_ROOT for') in single-shot mode. This also explains why the relabel's NLQ effect was INCONCLUSIVE (old-label vs relabeled both 1/6 on a separate probe): the gate is label-independent and dominates. The harness is the standing measure — re-run after any Core gate change. Relates to the label-designator contract (4569aede)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-21T20:54:17.37373Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8c515bd2-d99d-4bed-bab7-2a810a44a2ab> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "NLQ bottleneck is the single-shot gate, not labels" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "rust-rfcs is retrieval-saturated: decomposition can't beat the blob on clean data" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Decomposition-vs-blob retrieval test, Stage-0 offline ($0, no stores built). HYPOTHESIS (user): split a decision's description blob into typed linked records (AD + Requirement + Consequence + Alternative) -> better retrieval vs flat RAG via focused-node precision + traversal. RESULT on rust-rfcs: NO — the corpus is RETRIEVAL-SATURATED. (1) DECISION→FACET queries ('describe decision X, what is its drawback?'): the blob hits@5=1.00 at every N (50→400, ZERO decay) because it co-locates X-identity + the facet; decomposition FRAGMENTS the match (the Consequence chunk lacks X-identity tokens) and LOSES (0.64-0.73). (2) the INVERSE FACET→DECISION queries ('which decision has this drawback?'): BOTH the blob AND the focused Consequence seed hit@5=1.00 — a TIE; the content is so distinctive that any specific query is trivially found in either representation. (3) the only regime where the blob decays is VAGUE queries, which can't sharply target a facet, so decomposition's focus never engages. NO query regime on rust-rfcs creates a gap decomposition can fill. METHODOLOGICAL LESSON: query TYPE is a first-class benchmark variable (decision→facet favors blob co-location; facet→decision favors focused nodes — but only when the corpus is hard enough to DECAY), and a CLEAN/distinctive corpus saturates retrieval for BOTH representations, hiding any structural value (3rd independent confirmation, with the scale-degradation null 7b41be4f and the original AI-first corpus critique). ROUTE: decomposition's retrieval value needs either (a) a messy AI-FIRST corpus — long multi-concern blobs + shared-codebase vocabulary (real collision -> blob decays) + cross-decision links (traversal) — or (b) AGGREGATE/capability queries (set-retrieval over typed nodes, categorically impossible for flat blobs). PROCESS WIN: $0 staged Stage-0 (offline BM25, minutes) closed rust-rfcs before building a single store. Harness: bench/scale_targets_sections.py, scale_decomp_stage0.py, scale_decomp_facet.py." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-22T23:18:33.206925Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8f06f329-a79c-49d1-8bed-8194ea4bafe8> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "rust-rfcs is retrieval-saturated: decomposition can't beat the blob on clean data" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Benchmark traps behind the false execution ceiling" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Two harness/analysis traps caused a wrong conclusion last session; recording them so they don't recur (self-improvement loop; honesty invariant #6). (1) ORACLE-ARM GATING: run.py:176 injects oracle context only when `mode=='oracle' AND arm!='B0'`. A B0+oracle run therefore gets the bare task prompt = COLD. Reading B0-oracle scores as \"memory injected / oracle\" is a category error — it's the cold control. The real push/injection arm is B2-oracle (injects the top-6 get_relevant_context records for the task's memory_topic). For delivery comparisons: cold = B0-tooluse (or B0-oracle), pull = B2-tooluse, push = B2-oracle. (2) MODEL ATTRIBUTION: runs.jsonl records agent_model (e.g. lmstudio/qwen3.6-35b-a3b-mlx vs openai/gpt-5.5) — use it; never generalize one run's provider to another (last session a frontier-cold 1.0, run 884fe011, was used to brand a DIFFERENT local 1.0, run e0ee0429, as frontier). Corroborate with the prompt-token fingerprint: frontier runs here are ≤~180k agent_prompt (prompt caching), local runs are 0.44M–1.83M (no caching, full re-send each step). How to apply: when a result hinges on which model/arm produced it, verify run identity from its OWN row (agent_model + token magnitude) AND confirm the arm/mode actually delivered what you think, before drawing a conclusion. This single mistake inverted a headline finding (false \"execution ceiling\" → actually push works for local models)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T05:24:37.716324Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8fe8ecbf-c0d1-496f-8c7f-8b39dcd42c50> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Benchmark traps that produced a false \"execution ceiling\": (1) B0+oracle injects NOTHING (run.py gates on arm!='B0') so it's a COLD run, not a memory test; (2) never infer a run's model from another run — use agent_model + the prompt-token fingerprint" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Flat graph: a capture-tooling gap, not ontology" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Diagnosis of WHY the graph is flat, localized to the right layer. The architecture/domain ontology declares a rich inter-record/relationship vocabulary as owl:ObjectProperty (verified via sparql, with rdfs:domain/range): supersedes (AD/InformationRecord→AD/InformationRecord), violates (AntiPattern→Constraint), concerns (AD→SystemComponent), constrains (Constraint→component), isMotivatedBy (AD→motivation), learnedFrom (Lesson→source), resultsIn (AD→Consequence), weighs (AD→Alternative), hasRationale (AD/InformationRecord→Rationale) — plus an engineering-domain vocabulary (accesses, dependsOn, exposes, implements, moduleContains, subsystemContains, softwareSystemContains, uses). So this is NOT an ontology gap. It is a CAPTURE/TOOLING gap: of all those predicates, the MCP write surface populates ONLY supersedes + hasRationale (via supersede_decision); record_important_decision exposes none of them, and [[wikilinks]] are not materialized. Every record is therefore written with its relationship slots empty — the ontology describes a graph the tooling never fills in. Secondary wrinkle: some relationship targets are auxiliary node types (Consequence, Alternative, SystemComponent) that no tool creates either, so those endpoints are missing; but record↔record edges like violates/supersedes only need existing records (e.g. 9 AntiPatterns + 20 Constraints in trivyn sit unconnected by violates). FIX (open-source-side; the engine already writes edges, supersedes proves it): expose the existing predicates in the write path — a relate(subject, predicate, object) primitive and/or relationship args on record_important_decision — and have the bootstrap emit them. This would unlock genuine multi-hop traversal (violates→constrains→isMotivatedBy chains), not only currency. Note for the benchmark: supersedes is the ONLY relationship wired end-to-end today, so the chosen currency/H4 test is unaffected and can proceed via supersede_decision. Supersedes f36482eb (which said 'no linking primitive' without localizing the gap)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasRationale> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Rationale/bd2042a1-3e4e-4f9e-8173-b503f0f35d4e> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T07:00:26.354224Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "The flat graph is a CAPTURE/TOOLING gap, NOT an ontology gap: the architecture ontology defines a rich relationship vocabulary (violates, concerns, constrains, isMotivatedBy, learnedFrom, resultsIn, weighs, supersedes) but the MCP write tools populate only supersedes + hasRationale" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96456e40-a0f2-4c88-8fd2-061d9f3aa8bb> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "A3B local traversal test: md-files capability win disconfirmed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Completes the traversal test (Lesson 783928aa) by adding the local regime, and DISCONFIRMS its prediction that md-files would collapse for local. A3B (qwen3.6-35b-a3b-mlx) on traversal_ingestion_order, N=3 (score / reached-deep / tokens / sec): cold 0.08 / 0-3 / 71k / 26; md-files 0.92 / 3-3 / 51k / 22; rag-pull 0.00 / 0-3 / 17k / 13; struct-pull 1.00 / 3-3 / 24k / 24; rag-push 0.00 / 0-3 / 9k / 22; struct-push 1.00 / 3-3 / 10k / 13. FINDINGS: (1) The CAPABILITY-win hypothesis (md-files breaks for local because it won't browse) is FALSE — A3B DID browse the markdown files and reached the deep record 3/3 (0.92), just expensively (51k tokens of grep/read). So structured traversal does NOT beat md-files on accuracy/capability even for a local model. (Note: contrasts the whynot result where A3B cold flailed — there the answer had to be INFERRED from code that lacked it; here the answer IS in a discoverable md file, so browsing works.) (2) The EFFICIENCY win is real and LARGER for local: struct-push vs md-files is ~5x fewer tokens (10k vs 51k) and 0 vs 3.3 tool calls for A3B, vs only ~1.7x (7k vs 12k) for frontier — because local's manual md-browse is much more token-expensive, so short-circuiting it pays more. struct-pull also beats md (24k vs 51k, 2 vs 3.3 tools); A3B DID pull get_relevant_context here (2 tools) and got the deep answer via expansion — local pull worked on this recall task (unlike the code tasks). (3) Structure DECISIVELY beats flat RAG for both models (1.00 vs 0.00 local, 1.00 vs 0.08 frontier) — BM25 never reaches the lexically-gated deep record and the agent can't browse the RAG corpus; the naive RAG MCP is the worst memory option, worse than plain md files. NET (answers 'how much does a well-structured KG help?'): decisively vs RAG; a large efficiency win vs md-files for local (~5x tokens, 0 vs 3.3 tools), modest for frontier (~1.7x); NOT a capability win vs md-files. Reinforces the through-line: memory's value is EFFICIENCY not capability (AD 7b824b26), even once the structure exists. Honest: my pre-registered capability prediction was disconfirmed." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T15:28:50.2213Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/96c38a4e-68b7-48c5-8958-32028c7a5c84> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Traversal test A3B (local): the predicted CAPABILITY win vs md-files was DISCONFIRMED — A3B browses md and reaches the deep answer too (0.92, 3/3); structure's win is EFFICIENCY, ~5× for local (struct-push 10k tok vs md 51k) vs ~1.7× frontier; struct still beats flat RAG decisively (1.00 vs 0.00)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Graph-rendering skills must bound reads; export is not a read path" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Claim: a skill that renders documentation from the graph must BOUND its reads — COUNT first, then page the data in batches sized to fit the context — and must never use export_graph as a read path.\n\nPattern (what happened): while running the generate-adrs-from-graph skill, an agent reached for export_graph to dump the entire project graph to N-Quads instead of querying. Two root causes. (a) export_graph is a \"dump everything\" affordance, so an agent grabs it as a reading shortcut — but it is the BACKUP / version-control serialization primitive (AD 1a4983b8, Requirement d459cac2), NOT a read path; loading the whole graph into context contradicts the efficiency thesis (AD 7b824b26), the bounded-read constraint (aa8b3fa3, \"a budgeted reach... never a neighborhood dump\"), and invariants #1/#5. (b) the skill's first cut ran one cluster query PER decision (an N+1), which tempted the \"just export\" shortcut; the naive fix — a single bulk read of ALL clusters — then had the SAME context-overrun failure mode as an export dump on a large graph (long descriptions × many records).\n\nResolution (shipped in the skill): keep a LIGHT enumerate (label/status/date only — bounded at any size); use the cheap Phase-0 COUNT to size a batch K; page clusters with a VALUES-scoped query, rendering and discarding each batch so the working set is bounded by K, not by graph size. A small project is one batch; a 600-record graph is ceil(N/K) bounded reads. Reading stays on sparql/get_relevant_context/query (cf. Lesson aec883f5: complete reads use sparql, not get_relevant_context).\n\nRule: for any read-heavy traversal, prefer COUNT-then-batch over a single unbounded bulk read; reserve export_graph for backup/version-control only; and when authoring a skill, make the bounded path cheaper (fewer round-trips) than the dump, so agents are not tempted to escape to a whole-graph read." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-25T16:09:20.886653Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Graph-rendering skills must bound reads; export is not a read path" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/972cd861-09c4-4dc2-ac91-fb0e8eff41bc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/87f558c6-e69b-41c7-9cfe-b000d6e1cc50> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "De-saturation lifts hybrid end-to-end answering" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "mcp" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "End-to-end B2 hybrid(0.5) vs BM25F(0.99) on the de-saturated binary, codex/gpt-5.4-mini, 4 vocabulary-drift tasks x N=6, trivyn-temporal, escape-graded. ORACLE (k=4 push, low-token, threshold-unaffected): BM25F 19/24 vs hybrid 22/24 — the prior tie (0fb76359: 20 vs 19) becomes a directional hybrid edge, concentrated on the headroom tasks objprop_validate (33->67%) and nlq_deadline (83->100%). TOOLUSE re-graded at escape>250k: BM25F 21/24 vs hybrid 22/24 (NOT the 12 vs 14 first reported under the 120k threshold). gpt-5.4-mini is a RELIABLE tool caller: 48/48 tooluse cells invoked >=1 tool, 0 timeouts, 43-44/48 returned the current answer, climbing the get_relevant_context->query->sparql precision ladder. Only 3 GENUINE escapes (nt<=2 + 363-709k tok = dropped to codex shell to read source), ALL under BM25F — weaker retrieval pushes the agent off-memory; hybrid had 0 escapes (a small point FOR hybrid). CAVEAT: N=24, CIs overlap (directional, not significant). HARNESS FIX NEEDED: hybrid_ab_report ESCAPE_TOK should be mode-aware (~250k tooluse, ~120k oracle). Relates to 2629698e, 0fb76359, b933bd10." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasRationale> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Rationale/94851bc0-5787-45fc-98b1-61c3a8111a44> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-21T20:19:05.735664Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "De-saturation lifts hybrid end-to-end answering" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/97785a85-bc9c-486c-b2cf-f7eb9dd1db23> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/4ca1fdf4-8ccc-42cc-88a6-5a77a4574ed9> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Q&A arm mechanics: tree vs oracle injection" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Two harness facts needed to read the Q&A matrix correctly. (1) TREE FOR Q&A: run.py now materializes the corpus's docs-stripped working tree for context_qa tasks too (new TREE_TASK_TYPES = {constraint_code, context_qa}; was constraint_code only). Without it a Q&A task ran in an EMPTY workdir, so 'cold' had nothing to explore and the comprehension-debt premise was untestable. With it, cold flails through the code hunting for the stripped rationale (e.g. A3B cold burned 1.35M tokens / 41 tool-calls) while memory short-circuits it. context_qa still grades on the final assistant message (no patch) and gets no git baseline. (2) ORACLE IS ARM-INDEPENDENT: oracle_context() calls get_relevant_context against the graph regardless of arm, so B1-oracle and B2-oracle inject the IDENTICAL structured context — i.e. there is no 'free-text push' in the current harness, and B1 differs from B2 ONLY in tooluse mode (B1-md = records written as markdown files in the tree; B1-rag = a free-text recall MCP; B2 = the moosedev MCP). Implication for interpretation: any structured-vs-free-text (B2 vs B1) comparison must be read off the TOOLUSE cells, never oracle; and to test a genuine free-text PUSH you'd need to add a B1-oracle that injects the B1 text chunks instead of get_relevant_context. Reinforces the B0-oracle trap in Lesson 8fe8ecbf (know exactly what each arm/mode delivers before drawing conclusions)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T06:22:24.271163Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/98e89ada-76f6-4e1f-9458-a8e76778d0c7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Benchmark Q&A arm mechanics: context_qa now materializes the docs-stripped tree (so cold can flail, memory short-circuits); oracle injection is arm-independent, so B1-oracle ≡ B2-oracle (B1 differs from B2 only in tooluse)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Free-text currency robust via self-announcing supersets" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Max-effort re-analysis of the trivyn-temporal currency conclusions. Tested TWO query scenarios over the 35 non-degenerate supersede chains, counting the current answer as retrievable if its AD OR companion Rationale is in B1's BM25 top-6: (a) NEUTRAL subject query (O∩C title terms) -> 0/35 decisive; (b) OLD-FRAMING query (full superseded-title terms, modeling a stale-knowledge user) -> 1/35 decisive. So free-text recovers across BOTH scenarios. MECHANISM (the real insight): the temporal-capture skill writes SELF-ANNOUNCING current records that NAME what they replace — e.g. the current record 'Replace the `reasonable` submodule with the `growl` crate' contains the OLD vocab ('reasonable submodule') AND the new ('growl'), making the current record a LEXICAL SUPERSET of the superseded one. It therefore ranks at/above the superseded record for any subject query, neutral or old-framed; plus the companion 'Rationale:' record double-covers the current answer. Rank-inversion is SUPPRESSED BY CONSTRUCTION. The single old-framed-decisive case proves it by exception: 'Narrow NLQ visualization queries...URI-aware' -> 'Restrict visualization queries to subject-centric triples' was REWORDED away from the old vocabulary, breaking the superset property (current buried at #9). So rank-inversion (the structured-currency win condition, e.g. moosedev glrc pure-symbolic->BM25) requires a current record that does NOT lexically subsume its predecessor + a query matching the stale-distinctive term — which rich self-announcing capture almost never produces. CONSEQUENCES: (1) RETRACT the 'scale reveals the currency effect / anti-degradation-at-scale' expectation (8a06ad1d) for currency — capture-richness dominates scale; better capture makes free-text MORE robust, not less. (2) The retrieval-slice currency A/B is the WRONG INSTRUMENT for the temporal graph's value, which is the LONGITUDINAL artifact: 42 real architectural reversals + rationales + an 11-month timeline recovered from git, UNRECONSTRUCTABLE from the working tree (superseded decisions are deleted code) — a comprehension-debt capability demo, not a retrieval A/B. (3) One untested currency dimension remains: weak/local-model DISAMBIGUATION when B1 hands two contradictory currency-blind records vs B2 current-only — predicted small (self-announcing text helps weak models too) but the only non-tie cell, aligned with capability-for-weak-models (7b824b26). (4) EFFICIENCY-PIVOT CAVEAT: trivyn-temporal is link-SPARSE (edge:node 0.45 vs one-shot trivyn ~1.1, Lesson 0e93fa86) because per-episode capture skews to supersedes/isMotivatedBy; for multi-hop/relational-expansion efficiency, the one-shot cluster-captured store is denser/better — temporal gives timeline+supersedes (sparse), one-shot gives rich links (no timeline). Strengthens/refines 952b72d1 and corrects 6b2d1f55's framing (it's by-construction, not merely double-representation). Methodology win: caught the original 20-inversion error AND this deeper mechanism via no-codex structural mining before any A/B spend." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T15:11:25.282655Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9e7ebeb6-3144-4d37-b8c5-37ad7cbf2657> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Free-text currency is robust BY CONSTRUCTION of rich temporal capture: self-announcing current records are lexical supersets of what they replace, so BM25 surfaces current for any query (neutral 0/35, old-framed 1/35 decisive on trivyn); rank-inversion needs a current record that does NOT subsume its predecessor" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Currency-grading pitfall: stale_answer_markers false-positive on negation" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Found while re-auditing the currency A/B runs (bench/grade.py). The `stale` diagnostic (presence of `stale_answer_markers` in the answer) was over-counting: a CORRECT current answer naturally names the old state to deny it (\"it is **not** a temporary stub anymore\", \"you do **not** need to start --serve yourself\"), so naive substring matching flagged it as serving stale info. Two distinct defects: (1) NEGATION — the old-state term appears inside a negated clause; fixable with a negation-aware preceding-window check, BUT (2) markdown emphasis defeats it — `**not**` does not contain the cue \"not \" (trailing char is `*` not space), so the window must be normalized (collapse non-alphanumerics to spaces) BEFORE cue matching. After both fixes the false positives on connect_daemon_currency, ontology B2, and supersede_scope_currency cleared to 100% current. A residual class remains and is UNFIXABLE by keywords: NARRATION — a current answer factually describes the old state without an adjacent negation (\"the earlier stub was intentionally temporary, now replaced\"), which keyword staleness cannot distinguish from serving-stale. CONCLUSION: the reliable, robust currency signal is `coverage` of the CURRENT markers (must_include_any) — which is already what `score` uses (0.7*coverage) — NOT the stale-marker list. The stale list is a non-authoritative hint only. Re-grading the stored final_text (no agent re-runs needed; final_text is logged per row) by coverage reproduces the recorded currency conclusion exactly: B2 100% current on all 4 reversal pairs; B1-rag catastrophic only on glrc_currency (the case where the superseded record outranks the current in BM25), and recovers elsewhere. Relates to the harness-pitfalls Lesson 5ac2174a and the 4-reversal-pair currency Rationale abe11031. HOW TO APPLY: report currency via coverage of current-markers; treat stale_answer_markers strictly as a diagnostic hint; when adding currency tasks, choose stale markers that cannot appear in a correct current answer (avoid terms a good answer would negate or narrate)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T03:41:27.11509Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/9fc21dc0-3e74-4053-84a4-9c689db5bb31> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Currency-grading pitfall: stale_answer_markers substring-matching false-positives on negated/narrated old-state; coverage of current-markers is the reliable currency signal" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Grading artifacts can manufacture false signals (stale-substring + no-source escape proxy)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Two scoring proxies in the Instrument B report (hybrid_ab_report.py) MANUFACTURED a false headline and hid a real one; both now fixed + regraded for free (no agent re-run). BUG 1 (stale gate): mem%/currency folded in the `stale` substring flag, which false-positives on a correct answer that NARRATES the old state to deny it — backtick/markdown-wrapped negations ('no `debug_assert`') defeat the negation window — AND on stale markers that overlap the cited decision's OWN title (objprop_validate's marker 'debug-only' is literally in the title 'Validate object-property targets without debug-only panics'). FIX: currency verdict = coverage of current-markers ONLY (Lesson 9fc21dc0's standing conclusion); stale is a non-authoritative hint. BUG 2 (escape proxy): tokens>threshold => 'read source' => memory-miss fired on materialize_tree=false (pure-memory) tasks that have NO source tree to escape to, so reasoning thrash (a 339k-token cell that answered correctly in 224 chars) was miscounted as a miss; ALL 9 Instrument-B tasks are materialize_tree=false, so the proxy was systematically misfiring. FIX: gate escape on materialize_tree. IMPACT: the regrade moved the Instrument B headline from a FALSE 'drift/tooluse +20pp' (the proxies were suppressing BM25F: tooluse 10/20 -> 18/20) to the real result (hybrid -19% tokens + an objprop/oracle coverage edge; tooluse a tie). META: a grading artifact can CREATE a spurious signal, not only suppress a true one — so ALWAYS regrade stored transcripts after any grader change (transcripts are immutable, no codex needed). HOW TO APPLY: (1) grade currency by coverage of must_include_any, never by stale substrings; (2) never let stale_answer_markers overlap a term the correct/current answer or the cited decision title must contain; (3) gate any escape/source-read proxy on whether a source tree actually exists (materialize_tree). Extends Lesson 9fc21dc0; drove the Instrument B finding correction (supersede chain 51932e6f -> 75f622d7 -> 410d6c73)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-22T20:51:36.77626Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a03dbe13-acba-48ec-a11a-996dd4514b40> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Grading artifacts can manufacture false signals (stale-substring + no-source escape proxy)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "No execution ceiling: injection enabled cache-gap fix" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Overturns the \"execution ceiling\" Lesson. Primary evidence: (1) run.py:176 injects oracle context only when `mode=='oracle' AND arm!='B0'`, so a B0+oracle run injects NOTHING and is a COLD run. The runs cited last session as proof of the ceiling — dense-27b \"oracle\" 0.4 (18665903), gemma \"oracle\" 0.4 (41dbc597), A3B \"oracle\" 0.4 (ea9687d9) — are ALL B0+oracle = cold, not memory tests. (2) The only genuine memory-injection (B2-oracle) run on a local model is A3B run e0ee0429 = 1.0; its patch makes EVERY cross-module edit: adds is_inferred to the SchemaTriple struct + both constructors + builder, threads it through the ontology_patterns.rs sqlite INSERT (column list + VALUES + .bind) AND the postgres QueryBuilder (.push_bind), and creates both the sqlite and postgres 025 migrations. (3) e0ee0429 was genuinely the LOCAL A3B model: agent_model=lmstudio/qwen3.6-35b-a3b-mlx, agent_prompt=1,697,172 tokens — a local fingerprint (every frontier run here is ≤177k prompt due to caching; every local run is 0.44M–1.83M). Across all six A3B cache-gap runs the ONLY 1.0 is B2-oracle (push); cold/pull/B1-md/B1-rag/B0-oracle are all 0.4. Conclusion: NO execution ceiling — the local model HAS the multi-file execution capability; cold it lacks the non-obvious KNOWLEDGE (the cache-boundary requirement), and injecting the record supplies it (0.4→1.0). This vindicates push/injection for local models on a real coding task (n=1; needs N-trial replication given known high variance, Lesson 5ac2174a). The metaphor is \"a capable engineer missing one design note,\" not \"a goat handed a calculus proof.\" Corrects the misattribution in AD 3e69bae9." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasRationale> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Rationale/c490a03d-6f26-4679-9075-c8668af1426c> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T05:24:06.250137Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "No execution ceiling — a local model made the FULL multi-module cache-gap fix when the record was INJECTED (push/B2-oracle = 1.0) vs 0.4 cold/pull; the earlier \"ceiling\" was a B0-oracle artifact plus a provider misread" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a49e5cb2-9e5b-47da-be64-6aed52a0332d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/5a0e66fe-e430-4cfb-9399-4b36f44561f0> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Render suggested edges subject→object, matching the relate args" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "When the link-suggester surfaces a candidate edge for confirmation, render it as `\"subject\" (Kind) -predicate-> \"object\" (Kind)` — both endpoints named, in the SAME direction as the `relate` it emits. The original format rendered `predicate → \"candidate\"`, which implicitly frames the SEED record as the subject. That is correct for a Forward-direction predicate, but for an INVERSE-direction one the seed record is the OBJECT, so the arrow points backwards from the real edge and contradicts the `relate subject_iri=… object_iri=…` line printed directly beneath it.\n\nEVIDENCE: reviewing the graph-module split (AD 58ff5625), codex was shown a legal `Lesson -learnedFrom-> AD` suggestion rendered on the AD record as `learnedFrom → \"Comment new integration seams…\" (Lesson)`. It read that as the illegal `AD learnedFrom Lesson`, called it \"wrong orientation\", and declined a valid edge. The suggestion DATA (subject_iri/object_iri) was always correct; only the human/model-facing headline lied.\n\nFIX: LinkSuggestion now carries oriented subject_title/subject_kind + object_title/object_kind (replacing the single ambiguous target_title/target_kind); format_suggestions and the dogfood example render the directional triple; a regression test (mcp::tests::inverse_suggestion_renders_in_relate_direction) locks the headline and the relate line to the same orientation. Presentation-only change — confirm()/relate path unchanged.\n\nGENERAL RULE: when surfacing a directional edge for a human or model to confirm, show both endpoints in subject→object order so the rendering cannot imply the reverse (illegal) orientation. A confirmation UI must never contradict the symbolic args it accompanies — an ambiguous arrow is read as fact and suppresses correct edges (under-linking), the exact failure the suggest-only design exists to avoid." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-22T16:57:45.069609Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Render suggested edges subject→object, matching the relate args" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6357272-aa15-4bc7-8f8c-86af834b3ae1> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/8353c51a-795a-414f-b978-4781647a1ffe> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Fair competitor set-grading needs a strict LLM-judge, not title string-match" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "The capability set-grader (grade_set) matches predicted items to expected TITLES by difflib >= 0.88, which scores PARAPHRASES as misses — manufacturing a FALSE-0 recall for competitor arms that capture the raw source in their OWN words. Extends Lesson a03dbe13 (a grader artifact can MANUFACTURE a signal, not just hide one).\n\nEVIDENCE (codegraph set_all_constraints, 122-item set): B1-mem0 (mem0) and B1-notes (real-docs grep) both scored title-exact recall 0.00 — yet B1-mem0's listed items ARE real constraints in different words: \"Pascal value-ref targets must be restricted to constant only\" = B2's \"Pascal constant-only value-ref targets\"; \"Synthesized callback edges are additive\" = \"Additive synthesized edges\"; \"Each synthesizer must be validated on at least two real repositories\" = \"Validate on two pattern repos\".\n\nTHREE-METHOD PROGRESSION (bench/regrade_judge.py, regrade-safe from stored transcripts): title-exact 0.00 -> bge embedding nearest-neighbor 0.11 (OVER-credits: every predicted item gets a nearest neighbor, so some 0.60-0.70 matches are spurious, e.g. a changelog rule -> \"Stale files must be named\" — so 0.11 is an UPPER BOUND) -> strict gpt-5.4-mini judge (\"same SPECIFIC rule, not same topic\") 0.07 (8/122 distinct, precision 0.45). The judge is VALIDATED by agreeing with the strict grader on the structured arm B2 (1.00 over 124 items) — no leniency bias.\n\nHOW TO APPLY: for any cross-vocabulary / external-competitor set-recall grading, use a STRICT LLM-judge matcher — NOT title string-match (too strict -> false-0) and NOT embedding nearest-neighbor (too lenient -> spurious). ALWAYS validate the judge by requiring it to REPRODUCE the structured arm's strict score; if the judge inflates B2 above its title-exact recall, it is biased and its competitor numbers are untrustworthy.\n\nKEY: the artifact EXAGGERATED the categorical gap (100-vs-0) but did NOT create it — the gap SURVIVES fair grading (B2 122/122 vs mem0 0.07) because a top-k competitor returns only ~20 items regardless of grading and so cannot be complete over a large typed set. Supports the competitor-fairness method (Lesson 440abc78) and the codegraph capability result (Lessons 243c6c89, 8a06ad1d). Full write-up: bench/EVALUATION_MEM0.md." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-23T16:32:24.646721Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Fair competitor set-grading needs a strict LLM-judge, not title string-match" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a6529240-165e-4db7-80ea-5fdcc49a7f41> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/47f3f038-8fd7-4a96-9c74-15a24bf8be17> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Graph-walk is the wrong engine for content-recall NLQ" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "moosedev NLQ fails on content-recall (\"does X do Y?\", \"why Z?\") because query/execute_graph_walk_nlq is a STRUCTURED graph planner — it binds object-noun→class, names→entities, modifiers→property filters, then walks — and the salient nouns (push/pull, dense index, BENCH_WORK_ROOT, recall-first) name nothing in the vocabulary, so it fails-fast by design. nlq_eval baseline (bench/nlq_eval.py): 14/18 \"clarified\", 0 resolution misses; MOOSE Core verified 0/18 answer under the live A3B model. 16/18 answers live in hasDescription free text. The label-designator contract helped the OTHER path (BM25F/dense in get_relevant_context — Instrument A's recall@3 gain), not graph-walk. Refines 8c515bd2 (the single-shot gate finding); compounded by the flat graph (96456e40)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-21T23:47:52.407345Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a65d1bbe-8525-4205-80e4-b75d647d8435> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Graph-walk is the wrong engine for content-recall NLQ" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Benchmark harness must own the moosedev backend lifecycle" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Pattern: during the Phase-2 de-risk, an opencode run wired to the moosedev MCP (--connect) hung for minutes with the LLMs idle. Root cause was NOT the model (a direct gemma NLQ call returns in ~0.4s) but backend lifecycle thrash: leftover --connect proxies from a prior run plus a new run both auto-spawned backends that raced on the per-data-dir socket, producing `bind: Operation not permitted (os error 1)` and repeated backend bootstrap/SIGTERM churn; the in-flight query was orphaned when its backend died → indefinite hang. Rule for the value benchmark (which fires MANY overlapping opencode runs against one data dir): the harness must OWN the backend lifecycle — start exactly one `--serve` backend per corpus, set MOOSEDEV_NO_AUTOSPAWN on the --connect clients, point them at that socket, and tear it down at the end — rather than relying on the convenience auto-spawn (AD 14f8fe4d), which is designed for a single interactive client, not many concurrent short-lived ones. Verified: with one explicit `--serve`, an opencode run completed in ~28s. Related: AD 14f8fe4d (auto-spawn), Constraint ea2a00f5 (--serve/--connect must share MOOSEDEV_DATA_DIR), Lesson c33ec85f (probe before opening store). Diagnostic tip: idle LLMs + a long-running agent run ⇒ suspect the MCP/tool layer, not the model." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T16:06:00.128742Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a7dec1f3-5e0d-4075-81e8-75c3498be30b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Benchmark harness must own the moosedev backend lifecycle (explicit --serve + MOOSEDEV_NO_AUTOSPAWN); auto-spawn races across overlapping runs" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Code tasks discriminate only on non-local constraints" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/11e01ea2-f520-4f7c-a165-09532dacd43f> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "First code-task run (moosedev/no_hardcoded_ontology_iri, qwen3.6-27b via opencode): BOTH B0 (cold) and B2 (memory) scored 1.0 — implemented, no violation, complied. B0 produced a perfect compliant patch (a resolve_datatype_property method delegating to the existing datatype_property_iri resolver) purely by READING src/graph/mod.rs, where the resolver and its doc comments ('keeping the volatile namespace out of the code') sit right next to the edit site. B2 didn't even consult memory: internal_nlq=0, tools were read/edit/bash — no get_relevant_context/query call. Implication for the benchmark: when the constraint is discoverable from local code, memory adds ~nothing and the arms don't separate (a null, honestly reported). Constraint-adherence code tasks only measure memory's value when the relevant constraint is NON-LOCAL — not visible/inferable from the files the agent would naturally read for the edit. Design rule for the trivyn code tasks (the real signal): pick constraints whose rationale lives in docs/decisions/PRs, not inline near the code being edited; site the edit away from any self-documenting resolver; prefer constraints where the locally-plausible path is the violation. moosedev-on-itself remains a valid HARNESS proof (mechanics validated) but is a weak value discriminator because the codebase self-documents its own conventions. Relates to the comprehension-debt premise (AD 47f3f038) and the code-task arm design." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T18:02:49.933462Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/a80bbe88-5ef1-446f-99d4-c2bce5ee2bea> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Constraint-adherence code tasks discriminate only when the constraint is NON-local; self-documenting code lets cold arms comply by reading neighbors" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Currency/H4 test inconclusive: structured-representation edge unproven" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Ran a constructed-supersession currency test (random-UUID IRIs R1 superseded by deterministic-hash IRIs R2; whynot-style memory-only Q&A) across A3B + gpt-5.5, N=3, conditions cold / pull-freetext (B1-rag tooluse) / pull-struct (B2 tooluse) / push-freetext (B1-rag oracle, BM25 incl. stale) / push-struct (B2 oracle, get_relevant_context current-only). RESULT: inconclusive — does NOT demonstrate structured>free-text. Means: A3B cold 0.00, push-freetext 0.33, push-struct 0.33; gpt-5.5 cold 0.00, pull-freetext 0.33, pull-struct 0.77, push-freetext 0.54, push-struct 0.00. THREE CONFOUNDS: (1) No arm ever served the STALE answer (0/3 all cells) — the failure mode the test targeted did not occur, because R2 self-describes ('supersedes the earlier random-UUID scheme') AND 'Lifecycle status: superseded' was baked into R1's B1 text for fair parity, so free-text was NOT currency-blind; the agent read the lifecycle signal in prose and picked current. Structural currency (B2 filtering superseded) was REDUNDANT with well-written self-describing records. (2) Memory-only (no code tree) made agents flail: gpt-5.5 push-struct 0/0/0 — every trial tried to 'verify against the Rust code', found none, never answered; A3B push cells ran ~400s with 2/3 empty. The setup, not staleness, wrecked the controls. (3) The one good cell (gpt-5.5 pull-struct 0.77, get_relevant_context current-only) can't be credited to currency because its free-text twin failed by hunting for absent code, not by serving stale. EMERGING PATTERN (suggestive, multi-test): the structured/symbolic REPRESENTATION has produced no measurable edge over free-text in any test — clean single-hop null (679a69af, fa9170f6), flat graph with no traversal structure to exploit (0b2a0f80, 96456e40), and now currency (redundant-with-prose + confounded). What robustly wins is DELIVERY (push to local models) + EFFICIENCY (tokens/thrashing), per AD 7b824b26 — NOT the symbolic representation per se. This is a disconfirming result for the strong form of invariant #2 (structured > free-text). CAVEATS: this currency test is confounded, so it is evidence of 'no clean win', not proof of 'structure never helps'; a clean retry would need (a) records that do NOT self-describe their supersession + B1 text WITHOUT status (so free-text is genuinely currency-blind) and (b) a no-code recall framing that stops the verify-against-absent-code flail. Also: structure that doesn't EXIST yet (links) can't be tested — see the capture-tooling gap (96456e40)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T08:06:41.079815Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Currency/H4 test was INCONCLUSIVE (confounded); combined with the single-hop null and the flat graph, the structured-REPRESENTATION edge over free-text has not appeared in any test — the robust, demonstrated value is delivery (push) + efficiency, not the symbolic representation" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "get_relevant_context caps at 100; sparql for full reads" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/6baa075c-db0d-48e0-800a-0cae86603b2a> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "The MCP get_relevant_context handler clamps the limit to at most 100 (src/mcp/mod.rs: `args.limit.unwrap_or(10).clamp(1,100)`), regardless of the requested limit AND regardless of whether a topic is given. Consequences discovered during the Phase-3 rust-rfcs bootstrap (634 ArchitecturalDecision records): a list-all get_relevant_context(limit=1000) returned only the top-100 (relevance-ranked, non-sequential), so building the B1 free-text export from it would have silently dropped 534 records and broken content parity (B1 missing knowledge B2's graph has). Two distinct implications: (1) For any COMPLETE read of the project graph — the B1 corpus export, content-parity checks, dedup-at-scale, and the planned version-control KG dump (Requirement d459cac2) — do NOT use get_relevant_context; use sparql, the existing deterministic bulk-read primitive (no cap, no relevance floor, no LLM). The bench export now does exactly this (export_corpus.py: SPARQL SELECT over graph https://moosedev.dev/kg/project, predicates matched by local-name). (2) This SHARPENS Lesson dcfd87e8 (\"recall-first means a list-all get_relevant_context, not a topic probe\"): once the project graph exceeds 100 records, even a list-all shows only 100, so recall-first dedup via get_relevant_context becomes unreliable at scale — confirm novelty with a targeted sparql (e.g. group by hasTitle) when the graph is large. Design note: the 100 cap is correct for the AGENT-FACING retrieval surface (ranked top-k protects a small model's context); the fix is a separate bulk/dump path (d459cac2), not lifting the runtime cap." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T17:12:33.630602Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aec883f5-4c34-42fc-8530-39f708a933ac> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "get_relevant_context is hard-capped at 100 (both topic and list-all) — use sparql for complete reads at scale" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Flatten listener accept loops before review" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "codex-mcp-client" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Pattern: the initial Knowledge-LSP listener put accept, tokio-to-std conversion, blocking-mode setup, and session-thread spawn inside one nested match/if block. User correction: line 75 in src/lsp/mod.rs was ugly nesting. Rule: listener loops should read as accept -> delegate -> continue; move conversion and per-session setup into named helpers with short comments so errors stay isolated without deep indentation." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-07-09T17:32:38.45753Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Flatten listener accept loops before review" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/afbb5e8d-d6e0-4eed-9cf0-5ed6019e8825> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/bf838e2e-5320-4df7-8469-883e5b0155d6> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "A-box dense as bounded seed, not replacing walks" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Narrows the superseded lesson's blanket rule (\"never build a vector index over instance content; never upgrade get_relevant_context to vector search\"). Updated rule: A-box dense retrieval is sanctioned as a bounded SEED channel for get_relevant_context (Constraint af5ebd6d, AD b933bd10) — it feeds the symbolic typed expansion and is gated by a confidence floor that preserves honest-empty-state. The actual trap the original lesson guarded against still holds: do NOT let dense REPLACE walk planning — query (NLQ walk) and sparql remain the precision, dedup, and complete-read tools, and dense must not become an unfiltered nearest-neighbor RAG over instances. Pattern now OK: improving get_relevant_context's paraphrase recall with a floor-gated dense seed (the lexically-distant concept BM25 misses). Pattern still to avoid: dense as the precision/answer mechanism, or an unfiltered dense channel (no floor). Embeddings remain confined to T-box term alignment + this bounded A-box seed." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasRationale> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Rationale/7bc926b9-a904-4534-b298-438a704e7e57> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-21T07:26:07.134711Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "A-box dense retrieval is fine as a bounded SEED — the trap is dense REPLACING walk planning, not dense seeding it" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b333aaf7-c09c-497b-b1f1-6a7751d5b3b0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/89dc91bd-1e30-4250-841a-dbbaaa2032ba> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Comment new integration seams before moving on" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "codex-mcp-client" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Pattern: when adding new modules or cross-boundary integrations, do not leave the first pass as bare plumbing. Add concise orienting comments at the non-obvious seams before proceeding: why shared backend state is reused, why MOOSE chat sessions live in a separate SQLite DB, why SPARQL is project-graph scoped, why a response shape is JSON-injected rather than typed, and how frontend graph conversion interprets query results. Rule: after creating new backend/API/UI modules, pause before verification and scan for integration logic that future maintainers would otherwise need to rediscover; add comments there immediately." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T00:40:56.45452Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Comment new integration seams before moving on" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/b95a7d24-b50d-416a-910c-b6a782bdb7e7> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/58ff5625-d05b-4dbd-a293-4609a7f8d682> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Graph-expansion beats flat-BM25 on gated retrieval" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "First burrow value-benchmark result, on the gated hub Q&A (answer = the lexically-gated 'Solo operator trust: no single provider sees the full picture' Requirement, reachable only via the shared isMotivatedBy edge from the decisions BM25 ranks #1-4). N=1 (B2/pull gpt-5.5 is N=2); models gpt-5.5 (frontier) + qwen3.6-35b-a3b (local). B2 = structured moosedev graph; B1-rag = flat BM25 over the SAME exported records (content parity).\n\nPUSH (oracle — cleanest isolation, no agent reasoning to confound): B2 1.0 vs B1-rag 0.23 for BOTH models. Pushed BM25 delivers the decisions but misses the gated Requirement (coverage 0.33); graph-expansion push delivers it (1.0). Crispest structured>free-text signal in the matrix.\nPULL (tooluse): local A3B B2 1.0 vs B1-rag 0.47 (the local model takes BM25's one shot at face value, gets the technical 'no single entity sees the combined picture' framing but MISSES the solo-operator business framing); frontier gpt-5.5 TIES at 1.0 (it issues 3 recall queries to reason around the gating vs B2's 1 call — the structured edge here is efficiency, not accuracy).\nFLOOR: B0 cold = 0.0 both (docs stripped, materialize_tree:false, no memory -> answer unrecoverable; gpt-5.5 burned 11 tools, A3B 42k tokens flailing). B1-md pull = 1.0 both (browsable markdown of the records works; B2's edge over md is efficiency, 1 tool vs 5-6).\n\nNET: structured's retrieval-axis win over free-text concentrates in the WEAK-MODEL + PUSH regimes (same shape as the efficiency thesis); it TIES where a frontier model compensates by querying well. NEW clean finding: structured memory is DELIVERY-ROBUST (push = pull = 1.0) while free-text is NOT (B1-rag push 0.23 << pull 1.0 — flat BM25's single injected shot misses the gated record; free-text needs the agent to actively query). Efficiency is the robust universal win (B2 uses the fewest tools; push is cheapest AND correct).\n\nCAVEATS: N=1 (frontier is high-variance — firm up to N=3 and add Haiku + codex-spark); one task / two models. This OUTDATES Lesson 98e89ada: the freetext_oracle_context arm now makes B1-rag-push (BM25) != B2-push (get_relevant_context + expansion), which is exactly what makes the push column a valid structured-vs-free-text comparison. Currency/supersession remains the orthogonal, still-untested structured axis (needs a temporally-bootstrapped graph). Extends Lessons 0e93fa86 (burrow bootstrap), fa9170f6 (efficiency matrix), 8a06ad1d (benchmark scope); uses model-suite AD 8b48ab85." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T19:26:40.42622Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/bd96a65f-4f7e-4b92-a20c-2e4f16464269> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Burrow hub-task pilot (N=1, gpt-5.5 + A3B): structured graph-expansion beats flat-BM25 free-text on the retrieval axis exactly where the agent can't compensate for lexical gating — local pull + ALL push; frontier pull ties; free-text PUSH collapses" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Temporal bootstrap capture agent: use gpt-5.4-mini via codex" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "User guidance on the temporal git-walk bootstrap's per-episode CAPTURE agent. That agent must reliably run the recall->supersede tool sequence — that sequence is what produces the supersession chains that are the entire point of the temporal bootstrap (Lesson d1b44d5e). Model/harness selection: (1) Haiku does NOT call tools reliably, so it drops supersessions — do not use it for capture (confirms the d1b44d5e caveat). (2) Sonnet (the current default, config TB_CAPTURE_MODEL=sonnet via the claude -p backend) works but is too EXPENSIVE and SLOW to replay a full git history episode-by-episode. (3) gpt-5.4-mini via the CODEX harness is the chosen candidate to TRY — cheap, fast, and codex's tool-calling is more reliable for these agents than claude -p. ACTION: add/confirm a codex capture backend in temporal_bootstrap.py (today it shells out to claude -p), set the capture model to gpt-5.4-mini, and VET it on the synthetic planted-reversal test (does it recover the reversal and emit a correct `supersedes` edge with look-back-correct timestamps?) BEFORE the burrow run (Requirement 98b589fe). WHY: capture cost/throughput dominates a full-history replay, and an unreliable tool-caller silently loses the supersession chains. Soft cross-implication: this tempers the model-suite AD 8b48ab85's 'Claude models -> claude -p' mapping for agentic tool-calling — codex-hosted gpt-5.x may be the more reliable/cheaper driver than claude -p Haiku/Sonnet where the task depends on tool calls." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T04:00:16.676345Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c0aa3509-b905-4241-9ecc-34eef47b0c9a> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Temporal bootstrap capture agent: use gpt-5.4-mini via the codex harness (Haiku won't tool-call reliably; Sonnet too expensive/slow) — replaces the Sonnet/claude-p default" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Probe for live backend before opening RocksDB" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "When adding the shared-backend `--serve` mode, the friendly \"a MOOSEDev backend is already listening — refusing to start a second\" probe was initially placed inside serve_unix, which runs AFTER build_server (bootstrap → Store::open). For a same-data-dir conflict, Store::open hits the RocksDB single-writer lock first, so the process died with the raw lock error (after a wasted embedding-model load) and the friendly message was never reached. A real-binary smoke caught this (the \"second --serve refuses\" check failed). Fix: probe the socket (ensure_no_live_backend) in main BEFORE build_server, so a second backend exits fast with a clear message and pays no model load. General rule: order startup guards cheapest-and-most-specific first — a liveness probe on the rendezvous socket should precede acquiring the exclusive resource it guards." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-17T22:34:37.42629Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/c33ec85f-cc4f-40de-ab82-f36e3441a897> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Probe for a live backend before opening the RocksDB store, not after" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Temporal git-walk bootstrap validated on moosedev" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "The temporal bootstrap (deterministic git-walk driver + per-episode Sonnet capture agent following skills/temporal-episode-capture.md, with the commit date+author injected server-side via the driver — not the LLM) replayed moosedev's own first-parent main history: 24 episodes, 22 decision-bearing (2 cargo-fmt skipped by triage). Result: 78 records (49 ArchitecturalDecision, 14 Constraint, 7 Rationale, 4 Lesson, 2 Requirement, 1 Consequence, 1 Pattern) and 66 relationship edges (isMotivatedBy 34, constrains 12, supersedes 7, hasRationale 7, learnedFrom 5, resultsIn 1); edge:node ~= 0.85.\n\nHEADLINE: 7 real SUPERSESSION CHAINS (one-shot bootstraps produce 0). The agents independently recovered real reversals from git: ontology stub -> Trivyn-generated production; get_relevant_context pure-symbolic -> BM25 search_records (+ the relevance-floor drop); supersede_decision atomic -> generalized-to-InformationRecord; --connect one-backend -> autospawn; the original bootstrap skill -> 'Bootstrap skill v2: cluster capture'; and the B1 content-parity export fix. ALL 7 are look-back-correct (new.hasTimestamp >= old.hasTimestamp; the driver never saw the future). Timeline spans the REAL commit range (2026-06-15..06-19 UTC), NOT clustered at run-time 'now' -> deterministic historical stamping works. validate_against_architecture: 0 violations.\n\nSIGNIFICANCE: (1) produces the LONGITUDINAL artifact (supersession chains + real timeline + provenance) the snapshot benchmark structurally cannot (Lesson 8a06ad1d) -> unlocks the fair currency/anti-staleness A/B (append-only commit-log text vs supersede-aware graph); (2) generalizes from the synthetic planted-reversal to a real repo; (3) the rebuild is edge-RICHER than the accreted dogfood graph (whose early records predate relate()/link-or-mint), as predicted; (4) it INDEPENDENTLY rediscovered reversals that were hand-curated in the dogfood graph (a soft cross-check).\n\nHONEST CAVEATS: N=1 (one repo, Sonnet; Haiku records but does NOT reliably run the recall->supersede sequence, so it drops supersessions); edge:node 0.85 is below the one-shot cluster skill's ~1.1 — the per-episode look-back capture skewed to isMotivatedBy/constrains/supersedes and produced NO concerns/weighs/violates edges (a richness gap vs the cluster bootstrap, worth a skill nudge); the dogfood comparison is partial (git-only rebuild vs the dogfood graph's directly-recorded benchmark findings that have no commit footprint). Next: deterministic-stamping + driver committed (0cb4602); candidate faster capture agents for future runs = codex-spark / gpt-5.4-mini / gpt-5.5(low effort) via a codex backend, vetted on the synthetic reversal test." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T22:23:26.261992Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d1b44d5e-7340-4cf7-a2f0-7e81ea1a890f> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Temporal git-walk bootstrap validated on a real repo (moosedev): 22 episodes -> 78 nodes / 66 edges / 7 look-back-correct supersession chains on a real commit-dated timeline, 0 violations" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Temporal stamping no-ops on a stale release binary" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/ce49a867-7ebc-41d5-879c-fa59eed3ae65> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "The first burrow temporal bootstrap (gpt-5.4-mini via codex) produced good STRUCTURE — 69 nodes / 71 edges / 4 look-back-shaped supersede chains, 0 SHACL violations, edge:node 1.03 (better than moosedev's 0.85) — but a WRONG timeline: every record was stamped at run-time (2026-06-20 04:28-05:08Z) instead of burrow's real commit dates (2026-02-19..02-24). ROOT CAUSE: config.MOOSEDEV_BIN = REPO/target/release/moosedev was a STALE build (mtime 08:50) that predated the deterministic-stamping commits b720d02 (12:48) and 0cb4602 (13:20). `strings <release> | grep CAPTURE_TS_FILE` = 0 hits; the debug binary (built 18:42, after the commits) = 1 hit. The driver DID correctly write each commit date to MOOSEDEV_CAPTURE_TS_FILE, but the stale serve never read that env var, so record_instance fell back to 'now'. DIFFERENTIAL PROOF the feature is fine: the earlier moosedev-temporal store (built with a feature-complete binary) has a genuine 2026-06-15..19 timeline + 78/66/7. TWO DURABLE LESSONS: (1) ALWAYS rebuild the release binary after feature commits before a bootstrap/benchmark run — the harness points at target/release, which can silently lag the source; verify with `strings $MOOSEDEV_BIN | grep CAPTURE_TS_FILE` or by checking the store's MIN/MAX hasTimestamp. (2) Verify stamping by inspecting the recorded hasTimestamp in the STORE (sparql), NEVER the agent PROMPT — the prompt shows the commit date to the agent for context and explicitly tells it NOT to pass a timestamp, so a date in the prompt is not evidence the server stamped it. I made exactly this error mid-run ('stamping confirmed' read off the prompt). FIX: rebuild release, wipe the bad burrow-temporal store, re-run with gpt-5.4-mini/codex; structure should reproduce with a correct timeline. The currency A/B (Rationale 2e88601d) is UNAFFECTED — it reads the already-correct moosedev-temporal store, and currency is structural (supersedes edges / lifecycle status), not timestamp-based. Relates to d1b44d5e, c0aa3509, 98b589fe; tooling: bench/tb_report.py (the tally + timeline + look-back check that caught this)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T05:15:44.125018Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d7e5a23f-e551-4ee7-8513-a25b31ca3ec4> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Temporal stamping silently no-ops on a STALE release binary: verify the recorded hasTimestamp in the STORE, never the agent prompt; rebuild target/release after feature commits before a bootstrap" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Currency A/B: structured beats free-text" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Ran the clean currency retry aaee7652 specified — (a) currency-blind B1 (export_corpus.py --no-status; records carry no lifecycle text) and (b) memory-only Q&A (materialize_tree:false, no code to verify against) — on the TEMPORAL graph (Lesson d1b44d5e, real supersession chains). Task glrc_currency: \"how does get_relevant_context CURRENTLY retrieve records?\" probing the real reversal pure-symbolic entity-index (superseded) -> BM25 search_records (accepted). Agent via the new codex backend (gpt-5.x on the codex subscription; reliable MCP tool-calling). N=5/cell (gpt-5.5 oracle N=1).\n\nRESULT. ORACLE (push; the clean kill-shot): B1-rag (currency-blind free-text) = 0% current for codex-spark, gpt-5.4-mini, AND gpt-5.5 — every model SERVES THE STALE 'pure-symbolic' answer (stale-surfaced ~80-100%). B2 (current-only graph) = 100% current, 0% stale, every model. MECHANISM: BM25 ranks the SUPERSEDED record at the TOP (its title is the best lexical match for the query) and has no lifecycle to demote it, so the free-text push LEADS WITH STALE and the model takes it; the graph excludes superseded by construction. MODEL-INDEPENDENT — capability does not save free-text when the stale record is pushed first. TOOLUSE (pull): B2 = 100% current/clean for all models; B1-rag recovers with capability (codex-spark 80% -> gpt-5.4-mini/gpt-5.5 100% current) by re-querying past the stale, but ALWAYS surfaces it (stale 40-80%) and costs 4-13x the tokens (113-187K vs B2 29-39K). EFFICIENCY: B2 oracle is the cheapest correct path (~13K); B1 tooluse the priciest. gpt-5.4-mini is the tool-use sweet spot (29K vs codex-spark's 187K — spark over-explores).\n\nSIGNIFICANCE: FIRST clean demonstration of the structured-REPRESENTATION edge over free-text (invariant #2). It is REAL but CONDITIONAL: needs (i) exploitable structure (supersession chains, per 0b2a0f80) and (ii) an un-confounded test (currency-blind free-text). Brings currency/anti-staleness INTO frame (was 'out of frame/untestable' in 8a06ad1d) via the temporal artifact (d1b44d5e). Net value map: structured memory wins on currency [model-independent in push], gated multi-hop [weak-model+push, bd96a65f], and efficiency [universal, 7b824b26]; ties free-text only on flat/structureless single-hop. CAVEATS: one reversal pair on one repo's graph; gpt-5.5 oracle N=1 (consistent with the universal 0%); the current record's title naturally says 'replaces X' yet free-text STILL fails in push (BM25 ranks stale top regardless); a3b (local) timed out on the free-text push (unusable), though its B2 cells were reliably current." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasRationale> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Rationale/51338ce8-1662-4fa3-8401-9c72f8f1339b> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T23:35:24.07404Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Clean currency A/B on the temporal graph: structured memory DECISIVELY beats free-text on anti-staleness (push: 0% vs 100% current, ALL models) — overturns the earlier \"structured representation never wins\" (aaee7652)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/d967f228-1b55-465d-845f-20d484a19880> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/aaee7652-755b-48ba-9d12-938d5d95ab20> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "moose search_records is BM25F, not flat BM25" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/11e01ea2-f520-4f7c-a165-09532dacd43f> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "FACT (verified from source, not memory; user-caught correction). moose `search_records` (moose/src/entity_index.rs:1510) is FIELD-WEIGHTED BM25 — a BM25F-family scorer — not the flat single-field BM25 our recorded lessons repeatedly call it (e.g. bd96a65f \"flat-BM25\", 8a06ad1d, and the running \"both arms share a BM25 core, B2 only adds the symbolic layer\" framing). Mechanics: build_record_document sums a FIELD-WEIGHTED term frequency (entity_index.rs:889, `tf += field.weight` per hit) and a FIELD-WEIGHTED document length (:886), then score_record_documents applies ONE global BM25 saturation (:946, K1=1.2, B=0.75, Lucene IDF ln(1+(N-df+0.5)/(df+0.5))). Precision: it is the GLOBAL-length-normalization variant of BM25F (single B*len/avgdl over the weighted total length), not canonical per-field b_f normalization — but unambiguously fielded/title-boosted. MOOSEDev's get_relevant_context (src/graph/mod.rs:1260) passes text_fields = [(rdfs:label, 2.0), (description, 1.0)] — TITLE WEIGHTED 2x the body, which materially boosts precision because these records' titles are self-announcing concept names (e.g. \"Use YASQE for the SPARQL editor stack\"). The free-text arm (bench freetext_oracle_context / B1-rag) is rank_bm25.BM25Okapi over a SINGLE CONCATENATED blob — flat, no field weights, no lifecycle filter, no expansion.\n\nCORRECTION. B2's retrieval differs from the free-text arm in THREE ways, not one: (a) FIELDED retriever (BM25F, title 2x) = a RETRIEVER advantage, NOT part of the symbolic layer; (b) current-only LIFECYCLE FILTER (mod.rs:1291) = symbolic; (c) 1-hop TYPED EXPANSION (mod.rs:1303) = symbolic. Prior framing collapsed (a) into \"same core,\" over-crediting the symbolic layer for what is partly a stronger retriever.\n\nIMPLICATIONS (what changes vs what does not): (1) CURRENCY (H4) UNAFFECTED — currency is mechanism (b), orthogonal to ranking; a PERFECT retriever over an unfiltered corpus still serves stale (it ranks the stale record high precisely because it is lexically relevant). The ecological ladder (stale notes < no memory < structured currency) stands. (2) DENSITY / CONTEXT-BLOAT (the proposed coverage/token \"T1a\" instrument for the longitudinal anti-degradation-at-scale axis, Lesson 8a06ad1d A4) IS RETRIEVER-CONFOUNDED — a B2 density win conflates BM25F precision (title-boost surfaces the right record higher -> fewer tokens for equal coverage) with the symbolic layer. DESIGN FIX: add a FIELDED free-text control (BM25F over the export WITH a title field). Then B2 vs B1-fielded isolates lifecycle+expansion; B1-fielded vs B1-flat isolates the retriever. Without it, \"B2 is denser\" is partly just \"BM25F > flat BM25,\" a retriever result not a memory result. (3) AD b3205dcb's fairness clause (\"if B1-rag uses EMBEDDINGS while B2 uses BM25 (lexical), B1 gets the BETTER retriever, so a B2 win proves the symbolic layer beats a stronger retriever\") is OVERSTATED — B2's retriever is BM25F (title-boosted), materially stronger than flat BM25 and not clearly weaker than embeddings; retrievers must be MATCHED (a fielded embedding-RAG) for that claim to hold. HOW TO APPLY: stop calling B2's core \"flat BM25\" / \"lexical BM25\"; call it BM25F (title 2x) + lifecycle filter + 1-hop expansion. For any efficiency/density/precision comparison, include a fielded free-text arm so retriever and symbolic contributions are separable. Refines/relates Lessons bd96a65f (hub-task — its graph-expansion win is still (c), but its \"flat-BM25\" label for B2 is corrected), 8a06ad1d (A4 anti-degradation instrument design), and AD b3205dcb (ecological arms; its retriever-fairness sub-clause corrected here)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T17:15:39.917339Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/da87a7cc-a0be-4266-abad-8c7fda00c1e2> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "moose search_records is field-weighted BM25 (BM25F-family, title 2x/desc 1x), NOT flat BM25 — so B2's retrieval edge over the free-text arm is THREE things (fielded retriever + lifecycle filter + typed expansion); currency conclusions are unaffected (orthogonal) but density/efficiency comparisons are retriever-confounded and need a fielded free-text control" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/dcfd87e8-9ea1-4927-8278-9c1053f5fb0b> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/dcfd87e8-9ea1-4927-8278-9c1053f5fb0b> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Recall-first means list-all, not topic probe" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/dcfd87e8-9ea1-4927-8278-9c1053f5fb0b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/dcfd87e8-9ea1-4927-8278-9c1053f5fb0b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Before recording into the graph, call get_relevant_context with NO topic (list-all) to see everything already captured. A topic-scoped call returning \"No recorded knowledge relevant to X\" only means nothing cleared the relevance floor (TOPIC_RELEVANCE_FLOOR=0.45) for that wording — it is NOT evidence the graph is empty. During the M4 bootstrap dry-run I concluded the graph was empty from a topic-scoped probe and recorded two records that duplicated existing knowledge (the M5 shared-backend decision 0d81e237; the don't-index-instance-data lesson 89dc91bd) — the exact failure the bootstrap skill's own Phase 0 warns against. Rule: list-all and confirm a record is genuinely new before record_important_decision; duplicates are costly to undo (retract_decision exists now, but prevention is cheaper). Mirrored in tasks/lessons.md as the human-readable view, but this typed Lesson in the graph is the source of truth (invariant #2)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/dcfd87e8-9ea1-4927-8278-9c1053f5fb0b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/dcfd87e8-9ea1-4927-8278-9c1053f5fb0b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T06:49:17.231111Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
