<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/e80db883-7235-4283-aef2-34eddc4b961c> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#supersedes> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/8120780a-7042-46e1-be18-5662977baacd> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Direct store writes leave the dense index stale" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/3193c9a7-8f50-4af0-b0b6-f05ebaa23393> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "mcp" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "A direct oxigraph write to the project store (bulk migration / label surgery) bypasses graph::index_record, so the durable instance dense index (instance-vectors.db) does NOT reflect the change: build_instance_index's incremental check is by-IRI (record already has a vector -> '0 to embed'), not by-content-hash, even though record_embed_text = rdfs:label + hasDescription. BM25F is unaffected because EntityIndexCache rebuilds from the store on serve restart. Fix: force a dense refresh — delete instance-vectors.db and restart for a cold rebuild (logged 'embedded 137/137'), or re-call index_record per changed IRI. Surfaced relabeling 121 content-shaped rdfs:labels to short designator handles on the dogfood store (the MOOSE label-designator contract): rdfs:label -> short NAME (0 over 80c, max 77, avg 52), hasTitle kept the full original title (max 359c) so the migration is lossless and 'hasTitle duplicates rdfs:label' no longer holds but nothing reads hasTitle for retrieval. 0 SHACL violations after. See examples/relabel_apply.rs + examples/audit_labels.rs." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-21T19:09:26.064336Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f1f86296-8bdb-449f-81f2-eef4cdef2d8e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Direct store writes leave the dense index stale" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Dev-only friction is not a product gap" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "During slice-3 Zed acceptance, the extension's PATH lookup found the installed 0.6.3 release (no lsp subcommand) instead of the dev build - and the fix was a one-line project-local settings override. Proposed product changes (auto-writing binary overrides in init, version-checking in the extension) were scoped out by James: only developers working on moosedev itself ever run a dev build beside an installed release; users get binaries where PATH resolution just works. Rule: before proposing a fix, ask who actually hits the problem - friction confined to the project's own developers gets a README line or a settings snippet, not product surface." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-07-10T00:32:22.601586Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Dev-only friction is not a product gap" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f20d266b-0983-4f66-8daf-2e7a5598018e> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/a7fc1353-2b7a-42c9-ab64-bd0043e412f6> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Valid memory task: not default, not recoverable" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/402e5c0b-dc22-4063-84c6-6b9dd954d540> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Refines Lesson a80bbe88. A task measures memory's value only if its correct action (a) is NOT the model's default and (b) is NOT recoverable from the working code OR git history. On a clean codebase almost all code rules fail (b) — frontier models trace them (see the frontier-traces-code lesson). Truly memory_only knowledge is why/why-not RATIONALE for a DELETED approach (e.g. trivyn's \"the old data-to-TLO merge was abandoned because reconciling two ontologies through the shared top-level ontology is too coarse a join key — two unrelated classes both landing on a generic TLO class says nothing about sameness\"): the rejected code is gone, so it cannot be traced from the working tree. BUT the git-history check is decisive and was run: the WHY is absent from ALL 537 commit MESSAGES (zero hits for coarse / \"join key\" / granularity / equivalentClass), yet it IS in the committed design doc spec/referenceable-ontologies.md — and trivyn's records were bootstrapped from that doc. So a frontier model with the FULL repo + git history can in principle recover it (git-show the doc). Therefore, for a well-documented repo, memory's frontier edge is EFFICIENCY (one query vs mining 537 commits / 90 doc files) + RELIABILITY (knowing to look) + CURRENCY (supersession-aware) + DELIVERY (push to local models that won't mine), NOT unique knowledge. Memory's unique-knowledge value appears only when docs/history are absent, stale, or lost — the comprehension-debt condition the benchmark simulates by stripping docs from the agent's working tree." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T02:49:46.104873Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f2f4cd99-127f-45f5-9e02-b203351daa24> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Valid memory-task design: correct action must be neither the model's default nor recoverable from code/git-history; vs a frontier model with full history, memory's edge is efficiency/currency/delivery, not unique knowledge" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "B1 export dropped SystemComponents via hasTitle assumption" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "The bench B1 pipeline (export_corpus.py, parity_check.py) enumerated records via hasTitle. Fix B / AD 73918962 (label-property decoupling) made SystemComponents carry their label in hasComponentName, not hasTitle, so the export SILENTLY dropped all 8 SystemComponents (34 of 42 burrow records) and parity reported a mismatch. Separately, the chunk text now bakes in '# title' + a 'Lifecycle status:' line, so parity_check's exact body==hasDescription comparison failed for every chunk. FIXES: (1) export_corpus.py enumerates by rdfs:label — the canonical label EVERY record carries (including SystemComponents), the same field get_relevant_context searches; rdfs:label is a W3C standard (not the volatile ontology namespace), so binding to it is consistent with decouple-code-from-ontology-ttl. (2) parity_check.py checks the description is CONTAINED in the (intentionally richer) chunk text rather than byte-equal. GENERALIZED (extends Lesson 51b09e67): when a write-path is made label-property-agnostic (it writes each class's declared labelProperty), audit DOWNSTREAM CONSUMERS that hardcoded a fixed label property — they will silently under-select without erroring. For record enumeration, depend on the stable canonical label (rdfs:label), not a class-specific typed property." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T19:27:44.480336Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "B1 export silently dropped SystemComponents (hasTitle assumption) after the label-property decoupling; enumerate records by rdfs:label, the canonical label" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f30307ee-356c-4877-98f1-f64a92988b27> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/73918962-4171-4a97-b666-ae51f7958f80> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Capture surface creates no inter-record edges except supersession" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Proven against the dogfood (moosedev-on-itself) project graph via sparql: the ONLY record→record edges in the whole graph are `supersedes` (×8) and `hasRationale` (×10) — both created exclusively by supersede_decision — plus prov:* provenance. There is NO relatesTo / refines / dependsOn / extends edge of any kind. Notably, this session's dogfood records contain many [[wikilinks]] in their description TEXT, and none were materialized into edges — MOOSEDev does not resolve [[ ]] (it is a .claude auto-memory convention, not a graph mechanism). Capture-surface facts: record_important_decision accepts only title/kind/description/status (no relationship param); align_concepts/suggest_mappings link to the ONTOLOGY/vocab, not between records; supersede_decision is the sole inter-record semantic-edge primitive. CONCLUSION: this — not the bootstrap skill — is the root cause of the flat trivyn corpus (Lesson 0b2a0f80) and the structured≈free-text null (679a69af, fa9170f6). The bootstrap correctly captured high-signal typed records; it could not link them because no linking primitive exists, so MOOSEDev's 'living knowledge GRAPH' is presently a typed LIST + supersession chains, and the traversal/related-context portion of the structured value proposition is unbuilt. Scope note: zero supersessions at bootstrap is partly expected (point-in-time snapshot, nothing to supersede); and the bootstrap flattened at least one real evolution (the data-to-TLO merge abandonment) into a descriptive Lesson rather than a supersedes chain. IMPLICATION for the structured-memory thesis and for benchmark task design: supersession is the ONLY structural mechanism MOOSEDev can express today, so the currency/H4 'structural kill-shot' is not merely the cleanest structured-vs-free-text test — it is the only one the current product can support. Open design decision (candidate Requirement): give MOOSEDev a first-class record-relationship primitive (and/or materialize [[ ]]) so capture and bootstrap produce an actual relational graph." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T06:55:24.044356Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f36482eb-4fff-4049-ac81-8aa528033edc> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "MOOSEDev's capture surface creates NO inter-record relationship except supersession — so capture/bootstrap yield a typed LIST + supersession chains, not a relational graph (root cause of the flat-corpus finding)" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Distinguish canonical RDF export from convenience output" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "codex-mcp-client" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "User review correction from the graph-export implementation: do not describe every RDF export format as equally deterministic or version-control safe. N-Quads is the canonical dataset export because it preserves named graph identity and sorted quads are byte-stable. N-Triples can be deterministic only after graph names are deliberately dropped. Turtle is human-readable and serializer-shaped, not byte-canonical. When exporting multiple named graphs to graph-only formats such as N-Triples or Turtle, strip graph names intentionally and deduplicate by subject/predicate/object so the output is a true triple union rather than duplicated triples from each named graph. CLI export should also reject a missing store instead of letting Store::open create an empty one that misleadingly dumps 0 quads, and file-writing tool docs should recommend absolute paths for MCP clients." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-20T18:47:38.592194Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f84b4b21-3097-41ff-82b0-dcf609564ec0> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "RDF export surfaces must distinguish canonical dataset export from graph-format convenience output" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "MOOSEDev read cost is query-dependent: the 1.68M set-completeness run was an agent dump, not tool overhead" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "CORRECTION (user-driven) to the \"MOOSEDev efficiency downside\" framing. The codegraph B2 set_all_constraints run cost 1.68M agent tokens NOT because completeness is inherently expensive in MOOSEDev, but because the AGENT dumped records via list_mcp_resources (tools=['list_mcp_resources','list_mcp_resources']) instead of issuing a targeted SPARQL. The exact complete set returns in ~hundreds of tokens via ONE clean query (Lesson 392855d0: B2 tool-ceiling = exact SPARQL set, ~hundreds of tokens).\n\nTHE MODEL: MOOSEDev's READ COST IS QUERY-DEPENDENT — a DIAL, not a fixed overhead. (a) Targeted relevance via get_relevant_context is as cheap AND as easy as mem0's recall(query) — same skill floor, parity tokens. (b) Completeness/structure via SPARQL is cheap IF queried well, and is a capability mem0 lacks entirely. So MOOSEDev is a SUPERSET of mem0's read behavior, not a costlier alternative.\n\nTHE REAL DEPENDENCY (what actually gets robbed): AGENT QUERY COMPETENCE — \"depends how the coding agent uses it.\" A poorly-driving agent OVER-fetches (the 1.68M list_mcp_resources dump) or UNDER-queries (misses the structured advantage). mem0's genuine edge here is its TRIVIAL SKILL FLOOR (recall needs no query authoring, hard to misuse); MOOSEDev matches it for the targeted case (get_relevant_context) but the SPARQL power tier needs competence.\n\nTHE COVER (design intent, not yet measured): the active/push layer (AD 145af7e9; push plugin AD 03393c63) is meant to drive the RIGHT query, and the v3 symbolic-controller vision (Requirement 350c7f2e) puts the symbolic layer — not the LLM — in charge of querying, so the payoff stops hinging on the LLM authoring SPARQL well (\"LLM as sensor, symbolic layer as controller\", invariant #1).\n\nHOW TO APPLY: never report a high B2 read-token figure as MOOSEDev's inherent efficiency cost — attribute it to agent query STRATEGY and report the targeted-query cost alongside. For competitor token comparisons, compare like-for-like (targeted vs targeted); price completeness separately (only MOOSEDev can deliver it). Refines the EVALUATION_MEM0.md efficiency note; relates to Lessons 392855d0 (tool ceiling), 8a06ad1d (capability axis), a6529240 (grading fairness)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "superseded" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-23T17:14:33.356187Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "MOOSEDev read cost is query-dependent: the 1.68M set-completeness run was an agent dump, not tool overhead" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/145af7e9-c8ad-40e1-91ab-e4442d861733> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/47f3f038-8fd7-4a96-9c74-15a24bf8be17> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/f8f2f87c-4b2a-436c-abfb-23cf32e08cc3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#learnedFrom> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/ArchitecturalDecision/7b824b26-36bb-47ce-a235-0a4fdf31a662> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Q&A efficiency matrix: local push dominates" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "First clean delivery-vs-cost result on a comprehension-debt Q&A task (rationale doc stripped from the agent tree, no git history). Task: explain why the data-to-TLO ontology merge was rejected. Two models × conditions, N=3 trials, means. LOCAL A3B (qwen3.6-35b-a3b-mlx): cold 0.12 score / 681,987 prompt-tok / 24.3 tool-calls / 257s; pull (B2 tooluse) 0.00 / 820,174 / 24.0 / 375s; push (B2 oracle) 0.90 / 9,798 / 0.0 / 35s. → Push DOMINATES every axis (70× fewer prompt tokens than cold, 0 vs 24 tools, 1 vs 19 steps, 7× faster) AND is the only condition that answers correctly. Pull is ACTIVELY HARMFUL for local: 0/3 correct (worse than cold) and the MOST expensive — when the A3B engages the memory tools it thrashes harder (one trial 2.34M tokens / 61 tool-calls incl. 30 bash + get_relevant_context+query+sparql, still 0.0; one timed out at 600s). Handing a local model memory tools just adds ways to flail; the symbolic layer must retrieve (invariant #1). FRONTIER gpt-5.5: cold 0.70 / 49,616 / 22.3 / 67s; b1-md (ambient markdown in tree) 0.70 / 19,518 / 2.3; b1-rag (free-text recall tool) 0.90 / 7,882 / 1.0; pull (structured tool) 0.58 / 20,006 / 3.0; push 0.70 / 6,027 / 0.0 / 7s. → Frontier recovers the 'why' cold by exploration (0.70), so memory's frontier edge is EFFICIENCY not accuracy: at matched ~0.70 accuracy, push costs 8× fewer prompt tokens, 22→0 tool-calls, ~10× faster than cold. Frontier PULLS reliably (every pull/rag cell made its memory call), so the local push-only necessity does not apply — a single recall call (b1-rag) is the frontier sweet spot. TWO HONEST NULLS/CAVEATS: (1) structured (B2) did NOT beat free-text (B1) — free-text edged it (rag 0.90 ≥ push/pull 0.58-0.70) — the EXPECTED single-hop null (hop_count=1; one lookup suffices), reinforcing Lesson 679a69af; structured's edge needs a MULTI-HOP task, untested. (2) Scores are keyword-coverage-graded (paraphrase-penalizing): gpt-5.5 push 0.70 (rephrases) < A3B push 0.90 (parrots the record) is almost certainly a grading artifact, not worse frontier answers — so cross-model ACCURACY is noisy while the EFFICIENCY/THRASHING metrics are robust and comparable (LLM-judge is the fix, per the task spec). Net: token-efficiency + thrashing-reduction is the UNIVERSAL win (local 70×, frontier 8×; both 24→0 tools); accuracy is a big win for weak models (knowledge-gap closing) and a wash for frontier. Demonstrates Lesson f2f4cd99 (frontier edge = efficiency) with numbers; extends push AD 03393c63 and the local-pull Lesson 2dcca5ff (pull now shown HARMFUL, not merely ignored, for local)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "proposed" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-19T06:21:50.518133Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fa9170f6-ac97-4264-9c66-77eecf55e47d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Q&A efficiency matrix (whynot_tlo_merge, N=3): for LOCAL models push dominates and pull is actively harmful; for FRONTIER memory is an efficiency play, not an accuracy play; structured≈free-text on single-hop" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Pin the agent temperature server-side in LM Studio" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#concerns> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/SystemComponent/f4d2f589-8f00-4640-ae16-fbb0184cb365> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Benchmark setup finding. The agent-under-test runs via opencode, whose config exposes no temperature/top_p/seed (only timeout-type provider options and --variant for reasoning effort), so temperature must be pinned SERVER-SIDE in LM Studio (per-model default, reload to apply). MOOSEDev's internal NLQ client already sends temperature 0 (src/llm/mod.rs:116, unwrap_or(0.0)), so only the agent needed pinning. Verified empirically: before pinning, repeated B2 runs drifted (score 1.0 then 0.767); after setting qwen3.6-27b to temp 0 + reload, 3/3 repeats scored 1.0 with tightly clustered token counts — confirming LM Studio temp 0 is the effective control (opencode does not override it with its own temperature). IMPORTANT: temp 0 is NOT bit-exact determinism on local MoE inference — the three temp-0 outputs still differed in wording/length (different sha, len 584/609/498) due to Metal FP non-associativity, MoE expert routing, and batching. So temperature 0 collapses OUTCOME (score) variance but not token-exact output; keep N trials + mean±CI in the matrix for honest confidence intervals. Rule: set agent temperature 0 in LM Studio per model + reload; do not expect identical transcripts; report mean±CI over trials, not single runs. Relates to the 4-arm skeleton (Lesson 51f65b34)." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-18T16:49:45.524159Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/fcb8eb30-5c8e-49e8-bea7-ffcfcadda242> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Pin the agent temperature in LM Studio (opencode exposes no temperature config); temp 0 stabilizes the graded score but local-MoE inference keeps text-level non-determinism" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Lesson> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Dense index startup cost: cold vs warm" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "mcp" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Empirical startup cost of build_instance_index on the trivyn-temporal graph: COLD build embedded all 416 records in 107s (snowflake-arctic-embed-s, CPU); WARM restart on the persisted instance-vectors.db re-embedded 0 (serve log: '[instance-vectors] index warm (416 records, 0 to embed)') and the socket came up in seconds. Confirms the durable+incremental decision (b933bd10): without persistence every benchmark serve restart would re-pay the 107s cold build; with it, only the first boot pays and cost is proportional to churn, not graph size. Practical note for benches: pre-warm the index once before a matrix so the first cell is not skewed by the cold build." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-21T09:14:01.391968Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Lesson/ffb79129-53d0-436e-9317-2cbb5703183d> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Durable instance dense index startup cost: 107s cold build for 416 records (trivyn-temporal), 0 on warm restart — validates the durable+incremental decision" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Pattern> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Modernize a pre-GROWL store by re-serving, not re-bootstrapping" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Re-serving a pre-GROWL store with the GROWL+new-core binary materializes inverse/subproperty edges into kg/project on the FIRST read (AppState bootstraps inferred_stale=true; ensure_enriched -> enrich_now persists, idempotent), with ZERO change to asserted records or supersede chains — so it is the cheap, safe way to bring a stale store current vs a from-scratch re-bootstrap. Verified 2026-06-22 on three bench stores: burrow 46->92 edges (+46 inverses), burrow-temporal 54->112 (+58; 4 supersede chains intact), trivyn-temporal 186->419 (+233; asserted edge:node 0.45->1.01, 42 chains intact). The new MOOSE core full-text-search (#42)/search_records (#41) also applies at query time after the re-serve. For incremental COMMIT catch-up (a graph N commits behind main) use temporal_bootstrap.py --resume: a per-store temporal-applied.log cursor re-enumerates the live trunk, skips already-applied SHAs, and captures only the new tip episodes (assumes append-only trunk; cursor must travel with the store). The snapshot skill bootstrap-existing-codebase has NO commit cursor — it re-surveys from scratch." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-22T20:08:17.664703Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/613cb623-9ee8-4eaa-80db-c1e8e83b40f3> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Modernize a pre-GROWL store by re-serving, not re-bootstrapping" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Pattern> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Mine spec files for Requirements during bootstrap" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "claude-code" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "When bootstrapping a codebase, files clearly identifiable as specifications — under a spec/ directory, or self-identifying as a spec/specification — are a dense, high-quality source to mine for Requirement records. Specs state intended behavior and constraints directly, so they map cleanly to typed Requirements that downstream ArchitecturalDecisions can be isMotivatedBy. WHY THIS MATTERS: the dogfood graph is Requirement-sparse (~13 Requirements for 39 decisions), which is exactly why most decisions could not be honestly linked to a motivating Requirement during the link-backfill (anti-confabulation forced skipping them). Mining specs up front mints the Requirement hubs that make isMotivatedBy edges — and structural-NLQ traversal from requirement → motivated decisions — possible. Bootstrapper guidance (user-provided); operationalize in skills/bootstrap-existing-codebase.md alongside the decision-cluster capture phase." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTimestamp> "2026-06-22T15:02:22.252206Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a2bf1670-239d-40d4-8f7c-f87b095c0c90> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasTitle> "Mine spec files for Requirements during bootstrap" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a820e93a-131b-41fd-bb53-5bc4607ccb7b> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#Pattern> <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a820e93a-131b-41fd-bb53-5bc4607ccb7b> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Generated artifact pages use shared UI shell components" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a820e93a-131b-41fd-bb53-5bc4607ccb7b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasAuthor> "codex-mcp-client" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a820e93a-131b-41fd-bb53-5bc4607ccb7b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasDescription> "Generated artifact pages should keep common list/detail/archive/refresh/warning/markdown-navigation behavior in a shared UI shell component, while each artifact page provides only artifact-specific configuration such as API calls, labels, warning summaries, row metadata, and record prefixes. This keeps ADR and Requirements pages behaviorally aligned and makes future generated artifact pages cheaper to add without copying page-state and layout code." <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
<https://moosedev.dev/kg/Pattern/a820e93a-131b-41fd-bb53-5bc4607ccb7b> <https://trivyn.io/ontologies/software/architecture#hasLifecycleStatus> "accepted" <https://moosedev.dev/kg/project> .
